(105, 'Ashwin (ContextFort) <> Ashwin (Z47): Met Ashwin @ Contextfort. SMB just based off intrinsics. Should track to see how their thought process and customer backwardness plays out over the next 2-3 weeks. + High IQ + H&H. Also scheduled my call at 11pm Saturday “working all day round”. + Conviction + “I don’t see the reason to waste time at a job and not startup. Starting up is the only thing that makes sense to me” + Customer backward. But not a spike – spoke to customers with every idea, but only have 4-5 conversations. + Thoughtful approach to picking the right problem +/? Thesis – right no building in construction tech. a platform to help architects and GCs collaboreate better. Previously was focussed on security for AI, . i.e., prompt injection and so on. ? Very out of domain ? Need to get a read on resourcefulness – are they able to generate more conversation in a few weeks. ? team building +/? Refs – soft ref from Anand was good but he’s his uncle. Intro came from Anand (Uncle) Next steps: - Meet in the U - If this is not a conflict for Kanav, we can connect them for a chat – PD what do you think? Detailed notes Ashwin <> Ashwin,Z47 Sat, 26 Jul 25 Z47 Fund Introduction - Ashwin, partner at Z47 (formerly Matrix), shared background: My Startup Journey - Currently working on construction tech startup focused on contractor-architect communication - Previous startup ideas explored: - Background: Networking & Next Steps - Working schedule: 12-6 PM and 9 PM-3 AM - YC cohort conn...'),
(106, 'Notes:: Cookr Wed, 13 Nov 24 About the founders • Prabhu is the cofounder and CEO • Has a background in technology, worked at Microsoft for many years • Built Xbox consumer business and Xbox Live platform • This is his second startup, first one was in healthcare but didn’t succeed due to COVID • Other cofounders have backgrounds in food, technology, and packaging What is the business • Category marketplace for clean food and food products • Connects consumers with home kitchens for food delivery • Focuses on health, organic, and gourmet food products • Aims to provide home-cooked style meals through technology Scale of the business • Year 1 (FY21) - 96L GMV, spent around 10 cr • Year 2 (FY22) - 9.4cr GMV, total burn 16-17cr • Year 3 (FY23 target) - 20cr+ GMV, 30% take rate so Net Revenue 46-47%, -45% Net EBITDA, Burn 68L/month • Current monthly sales around 1.3 crores Operations • Initially had their own fleet • Now moved to 3rd party fleets (Porter, Dunzo, Shadowfax) • Facing challenges with Dunzo exiting the market and Zomato Blinkit pulling out • Building their own 3PL now • 52,000 chefs registered and waiting to be onboarded • 1300-1400 active chefs currently Consumer Insights • Core consumers: 28-45 age group working couples, 65+ senior citizens • Offers subscription meal services (30-day lunch/dinner plans) • Provides party meals for small gatherings (15-20 guests) • Menu focuses on home-style food not typically available in restaurants • Allows customization of meals W...'),
(109, 'Notes from Ambika Pande 2026-02-07T16:24:00.000+05:30: 1. Unfortunately haven’t really gone deep into the E-Rupi use cases so wont be too much of an “expert” here. But from what i understand, its not a hard to replicate product per se (you’d know this as well as me : public rails = limited infra moat) - so it really depends how cotodel is going after the market. If they’re trying to solve for “spend management” as a whole - then maybe could be the Ramp version of India, but the differentiation is definitely not going to come from E Rupi. 1. Another core problem (high level - this is just my understanding of how erupi works) is that the spend is constrained to merchant category. In India MCC code mapping is still a very real problem, every 3 months there used to be an issuing blowing up at Rzp regarding this. In fact - a friend recently went to sell a suite of products to Kotak, Kotak was the most interested in a MCC predictor product, since that’s what they still have a lot of problems in 1. Another point is merchant acceptance - my hunch is if it’s another method, the acquiring bank / PSP needs to also build that acceptance and integrations, how scaled up that is and if everyone offers - that’s something I’m assuming you’d know better than me :) but haven’t heard about it being a “big bet” anywhere or serious buzz created around it, so it’s either a small effort (which is a good thing) or not a focus area at all'),
(110, 'Product Overview: - Computer vision-based quality control system for textile knitting machines - System includes hardware box and user interface installed on each knitting machine - Detects fabric defects in real-time during production process - Reduces fabric wastage from ~1.5% to 0.1% through early detection - Currently covers 80% of common fabric types - False positive rate: 1-2 per day per machine - Each unit has 2 cameras for different angle detection
Market Opportunity: - Global market: 300,000 knitting machines - India market: 50,000 machines - Annual new machine sales: - Current focus markets: - Estimated global waste: $18B worth of fabric lost annually
Go-to-Market Strategy: - Two-pronged approach: - Currently prioritizing brownfield installations for next 6 months - Building brand recognition through “Nitai fabrics” certification
Business Traction & Financials: - Revenue: 7 CR expected by March 2024 - Current customers: 5 clients across India, Turkey, Uzbekistan, Bangladesh - Sold approximately 100 units to date - Unit economics: - First major customer (RT International):
Notes:: Overall: Maybe + EO: 5-6 | FMF: 5-6 | Thesis: 7 | Price: 8 ? Spikey : 0.5 Thesis and early adoption is dead center Worry how spikey these folks are, but usually a gap with this SaaS like archetype. Should rely on BRCs Slightly a capped a market to go after but if they can expand through the value chain, can outsize. Again goes back to Spikeyness Community cheque no brainer with Vasant & Nit...'),
